# [PCE](../wg/pce.html)

## Summary
The Path Computation Element (PCE) Working Group met at IETF 125 to discuss progress on Segment Routing (SR) extensions, stateful PCE enhancements, and new work related to optical and fine-grain transport networks. Key highlights included the stabilization of the multi-path extension, discussions on performance measurement reporting, and clarifications regarding Maximum SID Depth (MSD) and orphan LSP delegation.

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. Introduction and Administration
Chairs Julian Meuric and Dhruv Dhody opened the session. It was noted that several documents are nearing completion, including `draft-ietf-pce-multipath` and `draft-ietf-pce-sr-path-segment`. The chairs emphasized the need for more participation on the mailing list for Working Group Last Calls (WGLC) and adoption calls.

### 2. Stateful PCE and Multi-path Extensions

*   **[2.1 WGLC changes for multi-path](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-21-wglc-changes-for-multi-path-00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Samuel Sidor
    *   **Draft:** `draft-ietf-pce-multipath`
    *   **Discussion:** Samuel detailed changes from the WGLC, including stricter ABPNF for stateful PCE, terminology updates, and splitting the "Opposite Direction TLV" into protocol and operation sections. 
    *   **Feedback:** Adrian Farrel (Document Shepherd) confirmed the draft is nearly ready and will perform a final check.

*   **[2.2 Performance Measurements for SR-TE and MPLS-TE](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-pcep-extensions-for-performance-measurements-for-sr-te-and-mpls-te-lsps-with-stateful-pce-00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Rakesh Gandhi
    *   **Discussion:** The draft covers end-to-end monitoring for delay, liveness, and bandwidth. 
    *   **Technical Debate:** Andrew Stone raised concerns regarding the potential for an explosion of `PCReport` messages if statistics are updated frequently. He suggested investigating an alternative "informational" message rather than sending full state reports for every metric change. Rakesh agreed to explore this offline.

*   **[2.3 Amendment to Stateful PCE](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-23-amendment-to-stateful-pce-00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Andrew Stone
    *   **Discussion:** This document addresses "orphan LSPs" when a primary PCE fails. It proposes changing the requirement in RFC 8231 from "MAY attempt to re-delegate" to "MUST attempt to re-delegate" to a backup PCE to avoid proprietary workarounds.
    *   **Chair Feedback:** Dhruv Dhody noted this is a strong candidate for adoption as it fixes a known gap in deployment.

*   **[2.4 LSP State Reporting](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-24-lsp-state-reporting-00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Samuel Sidor
    *   **Discussion:** Introduces the 'X' flag (to indicate if a path was operator-specified or dynamic) and the 'T' flag (Transit Eligible).
    *   **Technical Debate:** Li Jant questioned if the 'T' flag was redundant with existing Binding SID (B-SID) RFCs. Samuel and Andrew Stone clarified that while existing RFCs handle B-SID allocation, the 'T' flag explicitly authorizes the PCE to use that B-SID in the computation of *other* paths, which is critical for scaling and policy.

### 3. Segment Routing (SR) Extensions

*   **[3.1 SR P2MP Policy](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-31-sr-p2mp-policy-00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Huaimo Chen
    *   **Draft:** `draft-ietf-pce-sr-p2mp-policy`
    *   **Discussion:** Updates include operational scaling considerations and liveness detection via Ping/Trace.
    *   **Feedback:** Dhruv Dhody and Zafar Ali suggested that the draft should focus strictly on PCEP protocol liveness (e.g., PCE-to-PCC) and reference other WGs for data-plane Fast Reroute (FRR) or Link Fast Availability (LFA) mechanisms.

*   **[3.2 SRv6 Inter-layer Network Programming](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-32-srv6-inter-layer-network-programming-00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Mingshue Wang
    *   **Discussion:** Proposes a new Node Address Identifier (NAI) for interlayer network tunnels. Dhruv Dhody requested the authors include diagrams/examples showing how a PCE uses this Tunnel ID during path instantiation.

*   **[3.3 SRv6 Policy SID List Optimization](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-path-computation-element-communication-protocol-pcep-extensions-for-srv6-policy-sid-list-optimization-draft-all-pce-srv6-policy--00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Zafar Ali
    *   **Discussion:** Aimed at improving MTU and compression efficiency by skipping redundant endpoint SIDs. The corresponding Spring WG draft has been adopted, providing the necessary foundation for this PCEP work.

*   **[3.4 MSD Consideration](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-msd-consideration-in-path-computation-element-communication-protocol-pcep-draft-ali-pce-sr-policy-msd-consideration-00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Zafar Ali
    *   **Draft:** `draft-ali-pce-sr-policy-msd-consideration`
    *   **Discussion:** This draft merges previous work on SRv6 and SR-MPLS MSD clarifications. It addresses how the first SID (which is often popped or not encapsulated) should be counted against the Maximum SID Depth.

### 4. Optical and DetNet Extensions

*   **[4.1 PCEP-LS Optical](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-draft-lee-pce-pcep-ls-optical-00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Lee Jant
    *   **Draft:** `draft-lee-pce-pcep-ls-optical` (extending `draft-ietf-pce-pcep-ls`)
    *   **Discussion:** Focused on reporting link-state for optical networks where BGP-LS is not implemented. 
    *   **Feedback:** Zafar Ali expressed concerns regarding overlap with BGP-LS. Adrian Farrel reminded the group that PCEP-LS is an experimental track, making this optical extension an appropriate part of that experiment.

*   **[4.2 Fine Grain Transport](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-42-fine-grain-transport-00)**
    *   **Discussion:** Extensions for FG-MTN (Fine Grain Metro Transport Network) topology reporting and path setup. Fatai Zhang (CCAMP Chair) confirmed that while data-plane requirements are handled in CCAMP/ITU-T, the PCEP extensions are firmly in scope for the PCE WG.

*   **[4.3 Bounded Latency](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-pce-slides-for-draft-xiong-pce-detnet-bounded-latency-07-125-00)**
    *   **Presenter:** Quan Xiong
    *   **Draft:** `draft-xiong-pce-detnet-bounded-latency`
    *   **Discussion:** Updates to align with DetNet (Deterministic Networking) architecture (RFC 8655). The authors requested adoption.

